But provisional driver’s licenses are, in my opinion, stopgap measures. The real issue is that—as a group—the youngest drivers are, by all statistical markers, simply not able to adequately handle the risks and responsibilities. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes even 18 is too young for a regular driver’s license. USA Today reports that Zuckerman has performed research suggesting a common desire among those under the age of 19-20 to take risks for the sheer thrill of the sensation. It makes sense then, to delay driving at least until the tendency to thrill-seek has begun to level out. If we continue to issue driver’s licenses to young teens, we will not only continue to see deadly accidents happening, but the death toll is likely to reach staggering proportions in the next few years. By 2010, the Baby-Boomer’s babies will be eligible to drive and millions of new teen drivers will be ready to hit the road.
Legislation dealing with this issue would be reasonably straightforward. Schools could continue to provide driver’s education classes to begin the learning process for future drivers, but no one under the age of 18 could operate a motor vehicle. A provisional permit could still be issued prior to granting a full driver’s license, and a certain number of practical driver’s training hours would still be required as well. The specific number of hours required could be based on the number of hours already required by the majority of states (in California, for example, that number is currently 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of practice with an adult.) Because the deadly statistics for teen drivers come from a cross-section of all states, uniform, national legislation on this issue would be a reasonable—and I believe effective—means of protecting teens across the nation.
The legislation I suggest is by no means a novel idea.

In browsing through the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, I decided to watch all the trick films, totaling fifteen from 1895 to 1901. These films generally take advantage of creative editing to produce illusions. My film study primarily focused on describing the poetics of the majority of trick films and examining the evolutionary outlier characteristics present in a few of the later films. Generally, the trick film at the turn of the century is stage-bound, composed within a frontal proscenium, features no camera movement, uses long and medium shots, and adheres to the strict one shot = one film methodology. However, some films at the beginning of the twentieth century dare to break these guidelines by introducing aspects such as multiple shots.
One of the most notable aspects that the trick films share in common is their filming in an interior set within the frame of a frontal proscenium. The camera does not move from its proscenium position to follow figures or objects. This composition was very common in early films, and drew its roots from the theatre and, for trick films, vaudeville and magic acts. One of the limitations inherent in the use of the stage is that figures in trick films generally only move side-to-side, and do not walk towards or away from the camera. Take, for example, the action in the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900). The actors enter from the right side and move back and forth along the horizontal axis. Even as they go out of the frame, the camera does not follow them.
The frontal proscenium style of composition also means that shots tend to be long shots and, more rarely, medium shots. Close-up shots are never used in any of the trick films from the Edison catalog. This borrows from the theatre and vaudeville tradition, where the audience would see the entire performance at any given time, framed by the borders of the stage. As in most early films, the actors do not move from the middle ground towards the camera, so close-ups never occur.
Generally, most early trick films follow the pattern that one conceptual shot equals a film. This limits the length of most trick films to about a minute or less, depending on the frames per second used. It also limits the dramatic or narrative usage of the trick films; most of them focus on short vaudeville-style tricks, such as magic, disappearing, and switching acts with little story. Note, however, that in a trick film, one conceptual shot in the viewer's eyes does not actually equal one physical shot. A single "shot" may actually be several joined together to produce the illusion of apparition or disappearing. Look carefully at The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), one of the earlier trick films. A more thorough inspection reveals the moment where the physical shot with Mary's severed "head" begins, even though the whole film is conceptually one shot to the viewer.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and ardent proponent of Republicanism. Although he was primarily an agriculturalist, his profession and brief career in politics made him known for his dedication and outspokenness on matters of personal freedom and government. His commitment to an agrarian system formed the basis for nearly all of his opinions concerning the government. It was his attempt to preserve and encourage what he considered the most superior of all careers that influenced his arguments on sovereignty, Constitutionality, and even the judicial system.

John Taylor believed that the United States had a great opportunity to create an ideal system because there was no native tradition to hinder the creators of the government, allowing for the establishment of a system of self-government. He believed strongly in the natural rights of man and in the fact that they are all interdependent—meaning that if one is denied, then they all will fail, and the value of those remaining is lessened. These rights should therefore be beyond the reach of the government. He claimed that what some called the “state of nature” meant that those with physical prowess and malevolent intelligence were the ones that profited, but that in a civilization, this must not be the way.

To create this ideal society, Taylor believed that a government must be made that accounts for the inherent good and evil inside of man. Taylor was very rigid in his opinions on a dualistic morality. He claimed that “As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human” (Ibid., pg. 167). He defined good principles as those that protect private property, improve agriculture, and discourage capitalism, and believed that a government founded in good principles would function equitably regardless of its administration, which would inevitably be led by avarice and self-interest. Self-interest, he believed, is man's motivation in all things, but that the trait is only considered evil when it leads beyond the creation of a society based on the public good to sub-societies that live at the expense of others. A good government was necessary to retain man's natural evil, and even then it must be under careful observation to avoid the addition of bad principles.

Taylor, like many other staunch Republicans of his time, called for a strict construction of the Constitution. He wanted an extremely limited Federal government, with no more rights or powers allowed to it than were explicitly stated in the Constitution. He knew that an extensive Federal government was expensive, and therefore likely to be despotic. However, he believed that a simple, literal interpretation was dangerous, and that without reference to the intent of the writers, such a method could easily become corrupt. Even more, he considered the Declaration of Independence the true charter of the United States, because it more explicitly describes the country as a group of sovereign states rather than one nation.

Referring back to Figure 17, there was a sudden decrease in commuter log submissions during the third month of the project, which was somewhat disheartening. The exact reason for this is unclear. With the onset of winter in a New England campus, fewer people commute by bicycle or on foot, which might account for part of the decline. Additionally, December marks the end of the fall semester when students are busy with final exams and grading, causing them to overlook submitting the commuter log. Furthermore, December also brings the holiday season and a month-long break for students and faculty, during which many do not need to come to campus. Classes resume for the spring semester in late January, which might also contribute to the low number of logs for that month. However, this does not explain the low number of submissions in February. One might speculate that any project like this may experience an initial surge of enthusiasm followed by a natural decline. To counteract this trend, we initiated the Carpool Challenge Week, a special campaign in March to boost log submissions, which indeed resulted in an increase for that month. One of the challenges we faced was maintaining project momentum despite both the natural decrease in engagement and the winter break. Another challenge in promoting alternative commuting projects is the deeply ingrained culture of driving cars in society. Therefore, offering incentives is crucial. We offered gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, an independent bookstore, and even some national chain stores. It would have been interesting to see if larger prizes like bicycles, hybrid cars, or electric cars could have further increased participation. Increasing the value of the prizes over time might also have helped. While the gift cards seemed sufficient at the start, announcing larger prizes like bicycles in December and hybrid or electric cars in January could have potentially increased participation and engagement instead of decreasing it.

An ETF (exchange traded fund) is a type of security that tracks an index, a commodity, or a basket of assets like an index fund, but trades like a stock on an exchange. It offers the diversification of index funds and the benefits of single stock ownership, such as the ability to sell short, buy on margin, and purchase as few as one share in any transaction. These benefits are very attractive, but the expense ratios of ETFs are significantly lower than those of average mutual funds. However, there are some drawbacks, such as the need to pay a commission on any trade involving ETFs, similar to buying a stock. Another advantage of ETFs is the wide variety of funds available. While these benefits are clear, it's beneficial for savvy financial investors to evaluate whether these benefits, like diversification, actually exist and to what extent. For this effort, we will examine the ETF IHF and compare it against the top 10 holdings that comprise the ETF to determine whether the benefits of owning a single ETF are close to those of owning a diversified portfolio of the ten stocks, and if there are better configurations of the same stocks that could provide a more optimal risk-return ratio.

To evaluate the ETF, it would be impractical to include every holding, so we have decided to focus on the top 10 holdings, which account for 63.58% of all the assets in the ETF. Below is a list of the top 10 holdings and their percentage of total assets.

To estimate how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF as a whole, we can use the current percentage of assets, normalized to 100%, to calculate the contributions of each stock to a portfolio's Beta and Return if the portfolio was made up entirely of these 10 stocks in the proportion established by the ETF's holdings. The calculations of Beta and return are included in the chart below.

From the chart, it is clear that the return of a portfolio containing only the top 10 holdings is 6.11% higher than the ETF, representing a 16% increase in returns. It is also evident that the Beta of the top ten holdings is 0.12 lower than that of the ETF as a whole. Based on the results so far, it seems that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could provide a higher return with a lower Beta. However, it is possible that the means of these two portfolios may not be statistically different from each other.

To determine if the portfolios are statistically different, the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks is calculated and normalized to 100% to compare their accumulated standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

Dream-land is one of Edgar Allan Poe’s self-proclaimed better poems. In “Dream-Land”, Poe uses the term “Thulé” in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott traces back to Virgil. Virgil used the term in reference to an island north of Britain, which the Greeks considered the edge of the known world. It is certain that Virgil did use the term, but there is a more contemporary source to which some credit must be given. Poe was very interested in German authors. This quote is important because it shows Poe’s familiarity with Goethe’s writing. Karl J. Arndt, in his book “Poe’s Politian and Goethe’s Mignon”, comments on the similarity between their two poems, concluding that Poe was imitating Goethe. The Oxford Companion to English Literature states that Goethe was a celebrated writer of the poetic drama Faust, which was published in two parts, the first in 1808 and the second in the year of Goethe’s death, 1832. Within the poetic verse of Faust’s second part lies a short poem titled “The King of Thulé”. The poem tells the story of a king whose wife dies after giving him a goblet. After her death, he begins drinking heavily and crying for his departed queen. He then decides it is time for him to die and gives his possessions to his children, except for the goblet. He then walks to a cliff, throws the goblet into the ocean, closes his eyes, and dies. The demeanor of the King of Thule and the description of the king in Dream-Land are quite similar, perhaps a dark doppelganger of Poe’s loss and crutch of drinking. Faust was also adapted into a romantic drama by H. P. Grattan in 1842, which was less than one year before Poe’s use of the term “Thule” in “The Pit and the Pendulum”. Poe references Thule twice in his collected writings. Once, he references “ultma Thule” in The Pit and the Pendulum, but he uses this phrase in “Dream-Land” twice, as bookends for the poem. “The King of Thule” and “Dream-Land” can be read as companion pieces. In “Dream-Land”, the speaker describes the landscape of Thule and how it is dark, lonely, haunted by dead friends, and sees a shaded world without color. All of these scenes would be interpreted as a reflection of Goethe’s poem, as Goethe’s king has just lost his wife, is lonely, and has lost his will to rule or even live. The entire poem is a description as if the speaker has stepped into Goethe’s poem. Goethe was a significant author who Poe would have known, aside from his respect for Tennyson. Poe had this to say when asked if he admired Tennyson: “Aside from the connection to Tennyson, Poe would have been exposed to Goethe’s work in the many reproductions that were taking place after the original publication.”

Under California law, could a customer who was injured after slipping and falling on an applesauce spill in a grocery store be awarded punitive damages by showing the store manager acted with malice because he was informed twice of the spill and failed to have it cleaned for a half-hour because he was eating dinner?

A judge is unlikely to dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages outright. To prove that punitive damages are justified, the plaintiff must present evidence that the defendant's actions were committed with a willful and conscious disregard for the probable harm that would result from the conduct, as well as demonstrating that the conduct was despicable. Palmer can argue that Martin should have known the probable harm of not cleaning the spill because multiple D&D customers were injured from slipping in the months prior to Palmer's accident; despite this knowledge, he still failed to clean the spill. While Palmer's argument that Martin's actions were despicable is less persuasive, it is still reasonable given the facts that six slip-and-fall incidents had occurred in 2009 and Martin still failed to take appropriate actions to maintain the safety of his store.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, Rich Wayne, an employee of D&D Markets, informed his manager, Paul Martin, about an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin told Wayne that he was on dinner break and "didn't have time to deal with customer complaints." At 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also notified Mr. Martin about the spill, and Martin responded the same way. At 5:30 pm on the thirteenth, the plaintiff, Jennifer Palmer, slipped and fell on the spill and sustained a serious back injury. Prior to Palmer's accident, five different slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D's in the year 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for compensatory and punitive damages related to her injury, and we are examining whether to file a motion for partial summary judgment against the punitive damage claim.

In California, a plaintiff can recover punitive damages for a breach of an obligation not arising out of a contract if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice." Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). The statute defines malice as conduct that intended to cause harm, or absent intent, the conduct must be "despicable" and committed with "a willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others." Id. at § (c)(1). Courts have characterized conduct as malicious when committed with a conscious disregard of the plaintiff's rights when the defendant "was aware of the probable dangerous consequences of his conduct, and that he willfully and deliberately failed to avoid those consequences." Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

Almost four years ago, I took a course on Islam at CBC. One of the main topics of heated discussion in the class was whether Islam is a hostile religion. I believe this question is more relevant than ever today. Looking back at events since 9/11, I've personally observed a shift in American mainstream media's view of Islam and extremism from hostility to extreme tolerance. I don't think in 2001 we could have had a presidential candidate named Barack Obama, who had an obvious Muslim background in his family.
The biography of the Prophet intrigues me because, according to what I know of the history of Muhammad, the biography contradicts his personality. From what I know and have learned in the past, I thought that Muhammad forced converts to Islam. He would conquer and take over tribes and then force them to adopt the Islamic religion. However, according to the biography, Muhammad was depicted as a kind of martyr, who was misunderstood and even humbled himself to others. After which, people started to see the 'truth' in his teaching and sought him out.
Moreover, there are uncanny similarities between the ministries of Jesus and the 'miracles' of Muhammad. The most obvious example is when he took mutton and milk and multiplied it so that there was more than enough for forty men. This style of writing makes me believe that the authors wanted Muhammad to be perceived as a humble prophet who did not need to prove anything, but simply lived in truth and miracles. This kind of fallacy is the worst because it downplays the miracle and life of Jesus Christ. To me, it seems like they are stealing and trying to take credit for the life and personhood of Jesus through Muhammad.
There are also many stories in the biography that seem to be part of their agenda to provide proof of 'witness' or how people 'spontaneously' converted to Islam. However, the problem is that many of these stories are at least from a third-party perspective. That is, the author illustrates that he heard these stories from so-and-so who heard them from so-and-so, and so on. I didn't like this much because, although their intention was to provide proof of the truth of the stories, I thought it diminished the stories and made them seem even more suspicious.
I think what bothers me the most about this work is that they try to exalt and lift up Muhammad as a godly man who was humble, endearing, wise, and gentle. However, history contradicts the idea that Muhammad was a gentle and humble man, and I can't help but think that if Muslims today knew the true history behind Muhammad's rise to power, they would react differently.

The teachings of Jesus and his beliefs during his lifetime were immediately left behind in the development of Christian thought that moved forward after his life. If we look at this history in broad strokes, we see a trend of Christianity straying farther and farther from its origin. It seems that today's world shows an ever-growing awareness and an unprecedented progressive tendency. While traditional people remain and will resist any kind of thinking beyond what was taught to them, this portion of the population may not be prominent enough to influence the whole. Among Christians, a historical awareness will grow immensely in future years. A yearning will spread, to distinguish the doctrines that were added into Christianity over time from the actual intent of the religion’s namesake. It may take decades or even centuries, but the outcome will be inevitable: There will be a great reversal in the trend of Christian history. There will be a progression back to its original form. A movement will grow in numbers that will remove layers of doctrine, one after the other, just as if the clock started moving backward, until nothing is left except a conception of what Jesus introduced to humanity on behalf of God, before any other thinkers made such claims. When this trend sweeps through the United States and Europe, influencing masses in its wake to worship as if we were living at the time of Jesus, following only his ideas, the church as an institution will remain strong to lead the way. However, because the theological clock will have moved backward, the extreme proliferation of diversity in Christendom will reverse into more and more uniformity of belief and practice. Between regions, between denominations, between divisions of every kind, we will see instead of differences, increasing similarities. Human history is filled with great reversions. Just one example is how Christians were at one time persecuted, shunned and killed by the Roman Empire. But later that empire became a Christian institution. Our country has gone from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The great reversion coming in our future will play itself out in the arena of the Christian religion, undoing history in search of the source, and undoing diversity in the process. It is crucial to note that part of what will make this process possible will be a method of reading Jesus’ words as metaphorical, and not as literal statements. So what is it that happened since Jesus’ lifetime? If we look far enough back into history, we find only Judaism, the theological beginning for the Christian religion. Monotheism, the perception of a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures, were all at the core of the religion by the time the Romans assumed control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population did not share one spirit. They divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots and a majority of common people.

I believe that The Jungle demonstrates how people are fundamentally greedy and self-centered. They only look out for themselves and strive to make their lives as good as possible, without considering anyone below them. The novel shows this in several ways. The most obvious area is the owners and managers of the large factories. All they care about is making their companies and factories as big and prosperous as possible. They do not care about anything or anyone that gets in their way or is harmed due to their advancement. According to Upton Sinclair's work, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world". Sinclair is trying to depict the immense damage caused by this pollution. He shows that the owners have no concern for any person or animal that might be hurt. They do not care about the massive plumes of smoke billowing out of the factories or the animal waste and urine runoff from the thousands of pens around Packingtown. The owners and managers also do not care about their employees working to make them wealthy. They would do anything to make or save an extra dollar, "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar". They force their employees to work awful hours and then, without any notice, might layoff multitudes of people at a time without any compensation or help finding a job. During the era "The Jungle" is set in, there were not many, if any, laws or regulations protecting the workers' safety or well-being. This allowed the managers and owners to run wild, forcing their employees to speed up production and work in terrible conditions. Although the book never says it directly, the people who lived and worked themselves to death in Packingtown were simply expected to deal with the horrible conditions both while working in the factories and living around them. There were no agencies or organizations set up to provide information or help to the workingman. There were unions that were formed, but these often did more harm than help as they made money off of the poor workers. The workers were so badly treated and had no way of escaping the system of Packingtown that they were described as slaves, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Many authors employ various methods to evoke specific sentiments or attitudes towards significant topics. Some techniques are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald utilizes these methods extensively in his novel "The Great Gatsby." Occasionally, he pairs adjectives with nouns in unusual ways to create a particular atmosphere around a subject. At other times, he assigns meaning to symbols and employs them for the same purpose. Fitzgerald employs this technique with numerous colors, including gold, green, white/ gray, and red/pink. In "The Great Gatsby," he establishes meanings for white/gray and red/pink colors and uses these meanings to remind readers of certain feelings associated with significant objects.

The connotation Fitzgerald assigns to white/gray is uniformity, with white signifying elegance and white/grey representing a higher social status, and gray indicating age and fading. He introduces this meaning early in the novel by frequently using both colors. Daisy and Jordan are consistently described as "in white" (8)—in fact, everyone wears white: Nick dons "white flannels" (41) at Gatsby's party, Tom sports a "white shirt" (36) when meeting Myrtle, and Catherine is "powdered milky white" (30). The only exception is when Nick gets his first impression of Gatsby's party: "the halls... are gaudy with primary colors" (40). Fitzgerald further reinforces these color associations by using them to color mundane subjects: as Nick commutes to work, he traverses "the white chasms of lower New York" (56), people at Gatsby's parties are listed under "gray names" (61), Catherine's apartment is "one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses" (28)—symbolizing uniformity. He also describes ordinary people or places as white or gray: Jordan and Daisy share a "white girlhood" (19), the "valley of ashes" features "gray cars" and "gray land" (23), the "Italian child" on the train is "gray" (26), and the dog-seller is an "old gray man" (27).

After imbuing white/gray with sufficient meaning, Fitzgerald employs them to signify indifference or uniformity, particularly in relation to Daisy. After a prolonged period without significant use of these colors, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as "dressed in white" in a "little white roadster" (74); readers begin to perceive Daisy as less of a character and more as a uniform object, something Gatsby desires and yearns for. Fitzgerald continues to use this technique around Daisy to reinforce the impression of her being a uniform addition, such as describing a "gray haze of Daisy's fur collar" (18) and her being in a "white" (115) dress before Tom and Gatsby's encounter.

San Diego County is known for its agricultural productivity, mainly due to its mild and sunny climate. Common crops include tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, stone fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a thriving market for organic community-supported agriculture in the San Diego area, with many local organizations having long waiting lists for organic products. Additionally, organic eggs and milk are highly sought after. Many organic farms offer tours of their operations, as well as opportunities for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This type of operation allows landowners to benefit from government programs while improving habitat, encouraging recreational use, and providing opportunities for farm tours and educational programs.

Organic farming often promotes greater biodiversity in both plants and wildlife due to the absence of chemical use. However, it can be more costly than conventional farming in some aspects. It requires more labor and management to control pests and weeds, and to fertilize the soil naturally. Organic farms often experience higher losses compared to conventional methods, and may lack the economies of scale seen in larger operations. Practices beneficial to wildlife, such as planting cover crops or removing invasive species, can also increase labor costs. Consequently, a landowner might seek financial assistance or expert advice to maximize profits and habitat quality.

The parcel for this scenario is located in unincorporated San Diego County, near the town of Potrero, adjacent to the Cleveland National Forest. It comprises 160 acres of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland. The land falls within the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan is currently under review, but it currently recognizes over a hundred plant and animal species, many of which are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, various butterfly species, and the California gnatcatcher. Other species are declining and may soon be listed as endangered, including burrowing owls.

The area has a long history of human habitation, with Native Americans living there for centuries. Later, it was settled by cattle ranchers and wood sellers in the late 1800s. This parcel was part of an original homestead patent and was likely used for grazing and/or wood production for many years. A real estate website was used to find this piece of property, and available government programs were researched to understand cost-saving and wildlife-friendly operational options for a small farmer. A local organic farm in the same area served as a model for what might be achieved.

Culture plays a significant role in any negotiation. Culture can be defined by what it is not, as much as what it actually is and what it represents. Culture is not homogeneous, nor is it a specific thing; it is neither singular nor uniform. Statements like “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating” are inherently broad and overly simplistic. While understanding a culture’s generalizations is appropriate, it is more productive for a negotiator to understand the significance of a culture to the matter at hand and how that culture’s attitudes can and will affect the table talks. When one approaches a foreign culture, one experiences it in a way that is relatable to their own culture, and comparisons naturally arise. Attempting to understand a foreign culture or mindset can involve anything from studying its history to recognizing its prejudices. Rather than judging or attempting to change a culture, one must simply accept it for what it is and work within its boundaries, especially within the scope of negotiation, and most especially if one comes to the table with a weaker bargaining position. Likewise, if a negotiator finds himself on “away” territory, a respect for traditions and beliefs can only help in getting over any cultural barriers and moving the negotiation forward. It is important to note that culture does not necessarily limit itself to a national/international dichotomy. Most companies within a given nation establish their own corporate culture. For instance, a corporate culture might emphasize long hours in the office or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of a corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, in communication style (direct versus indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, others restrict it to “company approved” charities or fundraisers. One need only look at the differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, intra-company diversity exists even from region to region, urban to suburban environments included) to appreciate the diversity of thought that can reside within a particular societal culture. Certain cultures are not nearly as stratified as American culture, and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but a similar exterior is simply a sign to dig deeper. Values are even more important to understand, because they provide the why of a culture. If saving face or communal harmony are valued within a culture, it is certain that a negotiator will not publicly shame his company or his superior in order to succeed at the negotiation table. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture which gives greater weight to a hard-driven bargain will not necessarily be driven to settle at the earliest opportunity. Taking these generalities into consideration is important before one gets to the negotiating table. However, a negotiator is well-served to learn something about his opponent on a personal level in order to make the negotiation effective.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” This phrase first appears in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible and is also found at the beginning of St. Anselm's argument regarding the existence of God. It is believed by the other author we will discuss, Thomas Aquinas, who also argues for the existence of God. Given that each of their arguments is in defense of the same concept, our task is to determine which argument is better. To simplify, we will assume both are correct in their belief in the existence of the God of the Bible. To compare their arguments, we must assume the same type of God figure. Neither argument, however, provides a comprehensive basis for belief in God.

To illustrate this, let's first examine St. Anselm's basic argument. Anselm's passage shows a path to understanding through faith, looking within oneself to find proof of God. He argues that since God exists in our understanding, we cannot fully conceive of His non-existence. While his explanation can be complex and unclear, the core idea is that proof of God lies within our own minds. He suggests that truth about God is found by examining what we inherently know to be true within ourselves. External evidence is not needed. This is often referred to in Christian texts as faith.

St. Thomas Aquinas, on the other hand, argues that the existence of God can be proven through reason and empirical evidence without the need for faith. This approach could aid in Christian evangelism by converting new believers through logical reasoning without relying on their willingness to accept unprovable beliefs. St. Thomas presents five logical arguments supporting the existence of God, including arguments based on change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. He demonstrates that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for His existence. If you know you are missing one puzzle piece and can assemble the rest, logic dictates you can know the features and existence of the missing piece without seeing it.

Some time during the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince who would later be called Buddha was born. Over the course of his life, he renounced the world and attained enlightenment, and his teachings led to the formation of Buddhism, with Theravada Buddhism being the most traditional sect. The religion is now around 2,500 years old; it looks different today than when Buddha was alive. This is evident everywhere, such as in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Both monks and laypeople participate in this ceremony, and it has religious significance, although Buddha never taught about such a festival. These differences extend from superficial traditions to the core beliefs of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, from both monastic and lay perspectives, has had to adapt its doctrinal principles over time due to both external and internal influences, both friendly and hostile.
There are several terms that will be frequently used in this discussion. The concepts of internal versus external forces will be mentioned. Here, internal forces refer to influences from members of the Buddhist community, regardless of their monastic status. External forces are those from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces are those that harm or intend to harm the Buddhist community due to a negative perception of Buddhism. Benign forces are those that do not intend to harm or help the Buddhist community but may do so accidentally. These terms will reappear throughout this discussion.
First, it is crucial to examine the basics of the religion—the core doctrines of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma consists of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist scriptures. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka includes the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka holds the metaphysical aspects of Buddhism. Metaphysical concepts include Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (inherent suffering), and Anicca (impermanence of everything). By understanding these concepts, one can escape Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which is continuous. Along with Sansara, lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion) will cease when one attains enlightenment. The Vinaya Pitaka outlines rules for life, with laypeople having five precepts (not killing, not lying, not stealing, no sexual misconduct, and not taking intoxicants) and monks following many more rules. The most fundamental doctrine in Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths: First, Dukkha; life is suffering. Second, attachment causes suffering. Third, suffering can be ended.

The United States of America and Mexico are a case of two nations that once had a long-standing rivalry that lasted 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. The peak of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the United States defeated Mexico and gained Texas and the American Southwest as new territories. There were many other conflicts between the two nations, which subsided just before World War I. The rivalry began with Americans and Mexicans clashing over key issues such as religion, culture, and tradition, and had a major conflict of material interests. This is not uncommon among nations that share a border, which often leads to rivalries. David M. Pletcher (1977) noted that "Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems" (p. 41). Both countries are geographically close to the United States and have been rivals, unlike many other Latin American nations that have enjoyed good relations with the United States.

Religious issues created a schism between the two nations, a problem that has plagued many nations throughout history. Sally Frahm (2001) stated that "if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy" (p.86). Similar to the Cold War's rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union, which included ideological struggles and competitions over vital interests, the rivalry between the United States and Mexico was primarily based on religious preferences. This distrust originated from the animosity between the English and Spanish, which hindered the establishment of friendly foreign relations between the United States and Mexico.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) identified 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during the 57-year rivalry period. Most of these disputes were territorial issues, including border raids from Mexican territory into Mexico and other frontier problems. Border raids by bandits and outlaws from American border towns were a significant issue that persisted until both nations exerted military force on their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97).

Schmitt (1974) explained that the rivalry began to dissipate as "Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way" (p. 109) and finally ended as "American ambitions changed from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico" (p.110) in the latter part of the 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I was suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I had never known existed. At the time, I was a nurse, having chosen this profession from a deep-seated need for safety and security that I had lacked as a child. The mantra I heard growing up was, "You'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick." So, despite my dream of becoming a scientist or journalist, I chose nursing.

However, here I am at 46 years old, single, with no financial cushion and unable to work. I've been disabled for 15 years, living on Social Security Disability and have nothing left to call my own. Each day is a struggle, an assault on my security, safety, and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore, but I know one thing for sure: I could not have made it through these years without the help of my family and a few good friends, no matter how strong I was. When disaster strikes, you feel anything but strong.

The point is that emergencies, big and small, will always be a part of life. There are no guarantees, and no matter how prepared we are, some things are too big to handle alone.

I agree that we should not rely solely on big government; its system is flawed. However, I'd rather see Americans trusting and supporting each other again, learning to help one another and ask for help, rather than everyone fending for themselves in their own backyards.

Conservatives often talk about "rugged individualism" as the backbone of our country, but the truth is, it was compassion, mutual respect, and the sharing of resources that kept our forefathers going. Pioneers crossing the Rockies didn't make it to the coast alone; they traveled in wagon trains.

So, by all means, be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit with first aid supplies, water purification tablets, plastic sheeting, duct tape for windows, flashlights, batteries, candles, waterproof matches, and canned goods. If you have the resources for a small farm, can or preserve your own food – do it. It's a great idea, as is a wood stove, as long as you don't live in an apartment.

But while you're at it, get to know your neighbors.

Why do organisms evolve in the manner that they do? Are there restrictions or constraints that influence the direction of evolutionary change? Although D’Arcy Thompson stated in 1917 that "even now the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms," the same can be said today. More recently, mathematical modeling has been applied to general aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis through both ontogeny and phylogeny (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our study is exploring how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic change in Prunum, in combination with experimental studies, can be used to elucidate the mechanisms involved in the direction and magnitude of evolutionary-developmental change. We used X-radiographic images of Prunum species to delineate quantitative parameters that could in turn be used to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were entered into the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995). We modeled hypothetical shell morphologies that could be used to interpret the boundaries of possible morphological change in Prunum. These results are being combined with experimental and descriptive studies in order to better understand macroevolutionary events in this clade.

A shell can be thought of as a structure that is a tube that travels over time through 360 degrees of space. These revolutions or turns of a coiled shell are called whorls, which are considered to spiral around an imaginary central axis. This axis runs through the central column of the shell and is known as the columella. The speed at which the whorls enlarge can vary, and a continuous line separates each whorl and is referred to as a suture. In most shells, the largest whorl of a shell is the last whorl (body whorl). The spire is considered to be all the whorls except the last. The apex is the tip of the spire and the opposite end is referred to as the base. The animal extends out of its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed in apical, basal, apertural and abapertural views. (The "usual" orientation of a shell is an apertural view, with the aperture toward the viewer and with the apex pointing up.)

A method for counting whorls is seen below. First, the shell should be viewed from the apical view and then it should be determined where the first suture begins. A line can be then drawn dividing the shell into two parts. Whorls are counted from this line, and are estimated to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be viewed as a series of apertures that travel through time and space as the animal accretes (i.e. builds) its shell. It is possible to trace the path of the aperture via coordinates of the center of each whorl’s aperture as well as the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture.

This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented. Once a mathematical formulation is made, it is then possible to vary parameters and modify the mollusk’s skeletogenesis.

The neonatal and infant mortality rates in Indonesia have remained relatively stable over the past decade. While the country is on track to meet several Millennium Development Goals, such as the water and sanitation targets, the improvements in child and maternal health rates fall far short of the targets set for 2015. The underlying reasons for these shortcomings will be discussed below, indicating a need to bolster the overall health system rather than focus on targeted interventions.

Indonesia has made progress in the number of births attended by skilled health workers, with 72% of births now meeting this target. However, this category includes traditional workers such as midwives, who cannot provide medical interventions during complicated pregnancies, leading to a high percentage of maternal deaths from hemorrhage. Therefore, the improvements in this particular indicator are somewhat misleading, and there is still much work to be done. Additionally, there has been a decline in the percentage of diarrheal cases in children under five years treated by a health professional. While data on postnatal care is incomplete, it is evident that this area is also a concern, with low rates across the country.

Cesarean-section rates remain below expected levels, at around 4%. These rates also highlight another significant issue: while the rate is 7% in urban areas, it is only 2% in rural areas, indicating a problem with healthcare service equity. Clearly, access to healthcare services is concentrated in urban areas. Another access-related issue is vertical equity, with a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles. This suggests that the poor find it much more difficult to access healthcare services, likely due to out-of-pocket costs.

When considering the next steps towards improving neonatal and maternal care indicators, the most fundamental question is how to most effectively address the lack of service. Specifically, should Indonesia prioritize program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall health system without focusing on pre and post-pregnancy care for mothers and children? There is no doubt that programmatic approaches to address the above-listed problems are appealing. Not only do "vertical approaches" that target specific health sectors have clear, manageable objectives, but they also generally yield faster results. However, there are some drawbacks to consider. One major concern is that investing heavily in programs for specific health areas can lead to other areas suffering from lack of funding and human resources being drawn to the better-funded sectors (as seen with international funding for HIV/AIDS affecting the family planning sector). Additionally, running multiple parallel programs for the same area can result in duplicated services that are also uncoordinated, leading to increased paperwork for supplies and funding.

Victorian novels are known for their meticulous attention to detail and their focus on the aristocracy of that era. Two novels that deviate from this trend are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. Both of these novels incorporate an element of mystery and a penchant for the unconventional, which is atypical of the period. This strengthens the characters and provides insight into their motivations and emotions.

“And now, clouds of bewildering and confusing ideas flooded his mind. He seemed to be still walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were arguing angrily: the very words they spoke echoed in his ears; and when he focused his attention on himself, … he realized that he was talking to them. Suddenly, he jumped back at the sound of gunfire; and there rose into the air loud cries and shouts; lights flashed before his eyes, and chaos reigned as some unseen force hurriedly bore him away. Through all these rapid visions, there ran an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain, which tormented him incessantly.”

The two novels employ this mystery often through dream sequences or dreamlike states, with the content and function varying in each specific case. In Oliver Twist, these strange occurrences frequently reveal some insight into Oliver’s inner self, the things that pained him, and his awareness of the true nature of the events unfolding around him. When the shooting of Oliver is revisited in chapter 28, Oliver relives the event vividly, as if in a dream, while he struggles to find help (see left). The passage underscores Oliver’s lack of control over the events that unfolded, as well as the dire state his health had reached. This is strongly present through Oliver’s hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting overwhelmed him; all his senses were numbed, and he did not notice the “unseen hand” that bore him away; he experienced his despair again, removed from the shock of pain, as the pain was now constant and linked with fear rather than surprise. With Oliver being overwhelmed, the question arises about whose will brought about his misfortune, because it was certainly not his own. This shooting reinforces the notion that Oliver had little control over anything; he could not even attempt to gain control of an event’s outcome, even while his life was in danger. A growing sense of defeat in Oliver is also implied here, as if old Fagin had begun to break him, forcing him into accepting this despair and influencing his ability to react. Otherwise, it can be assumed that Oliver would have made some effort, at least simply for the sake of his own life.

“The days passed – day! There was no day; it came and went as quickly as the night, which seemed so long and yet so short; long in its dreadful silence and short in its fleeting moments.”

A couple of years ago, I was involved in an after-school program tutoring elementary age students. I tried to help them with whatever subjects they were struggling in, but my strengths were in English and reading. I was recruited by one of the instructors to assist a young boy named Adrian, who was having a lot of trouble reading. I realized something was wrong; he had the most unusual problems. Some letters he could pronounce perfectly, while others he couldn't even get close to. He was of Latino descent, and I knew he spoke perfect English, but his reading issues seemed perplexing. We struggled, and it wasn't until I met his mother that I understood the problem. She didn't speak any English, only Spanish. With my limited knowledge of Spanish, we managed to communicate. It was then that it dawned on me: Adrian could read fine; he just didn't know the English alphabet very well. I don't know if that revelation helped him much, but I hope he's doing better now.

I share this story to address the issue of the language barrier in schools, especially in California. It also serves to illustrate that the problem isn't always as apparent as we might think. Even for a child who speaks perfect English, reading it can still be a significant obstacle. We all agree this problem exists, so what do we do? In Adrian's case, the solution was relatively simple: tutoring in English reading, particularly the alphabet and pronunciations. But for many children who barely speak English, the solution is much more complex. There is no one answer. The dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes—none of these alone will solve the problem. The key is to combine all of these approaches.

Firstly, the dual language system is a great idea. It's not just for children whose first language is Spanish, but for all children. Studies have shown that children in two-way bilingual education programs outperform their peers academically. Many people fear this idea, thinking it's a waste of resources and that most children will not benefit. This is false. If we implemented these programs in the classroom as the rule, rather than the exception, all children would benefit from it. How do we go about this, though? Do we require all teachers to be bilingual? No, that would be unreasonable and unrealistic. However, I do believe we can have special aides, tutors, or whatever they are called, who are bilingual.

From the moment we are children, we are often told that there is something larger than ourselves and our understanding. Some of us attend Sunday school to learn about it, others visit temples, or seek answers within ourselves. Many of us readily accept the faiths passed down by our parents, but some reject them, believing nothing exists beyond our personal perspective. We may switch from one set of values to another. Regardless of our path, we strive to define part of ourselves through our unique spiritual outlooks. We search for light in the dark to guide us out of the shadows and into the sun.

"Cardinals," my father replied when I asked him about his favorite birds. We sat on the front porch of our house, listening to the rain drumming on the tin roof above as we shared cigarettes. The rainwater gushed through the gutters, drowning the plants along the porch's edge. He gazed out into the rain, his eyes filled with a mix of searching and reminiscing. He had grown thinner over the past few months, and his clothes hung loosely on his frame. His hair had become thinner and sparser than I remembered. He stared out into the rain, deliberately avoiding eye contact. I felt alone, scared, and unable to talk to my father about how much I would miss him. Talking about it would only make it more real for both of us. I hugged him, sat back down, moved my chair closer to his, and joined him in watching the falling rain of the June evening.

My father passed away in December that year, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemotherapy and radiation did not alleviate my father's suffering, but extended his life a few more months than the doctors had predicted; I struggled to find value in that. What kind of God would do this, I thought. Alone in the night, I said no prayers. If God existed, I believed he had stopped listening to me long ago.

I did not want to witness my father's transition from life to death. So, I did not. I could not watch the life that brought me into this world as it ended. I wanted to remember my father by how he lived, not how he died. Besides, I knew my father better than anyone else, better than his family, and I knew he would not want me to be a spectator at his death. I curled up in a ball in my bed for three days, waiting for the news.

No one even called me.

The traditional Gothic Novel, in both name and essence, is an "oxymoron for 'Old-New,'" as described by Ian Watt in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. The Gothic mode has been both lauded and disparaged, accused of lacking depth, and praised for its 'terrible sublime' aspect. The original Gothic Novel, Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, fused ideas from both "ancient and modern" romances to create the proto-Gothic genre and a new literary method. Walpole used "old" theatrical elements and 'new' mimetic techniques to present a "Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre incorporates many medieval Gothic theatre, architecture, and tradition elements. Even when The Castle of Otranto was published, the term "Gothic" was used to describe various peoples, styles, and periods, often seen as archaic or unsophisticated compared to "modern" societal and literary advancements. The fusion of the more theatrical "Gothic" and the new novel format, allowing for a more personal exploration of character psychology, has kept Gothic relevant for a long time, making it both obsolete and fresh for readers centuries removed from its original publication.

One prominent Gothic theme is the concept of Chivalry. The medieval idea of chivalry, training a proper knight, is retained and transformed in The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry is significant to Gothic writers due to the ideal of the classic knight—brave, honorable, and competent—and the perceived lack of these qualities in contemporary society. By incorporating chivalric elements and manners, the "Gothic past" is idealized and romanticized, hinting at the Gothic's eventual evolution into Romanticism and serving as a means to aspire to improve the present. Walpole wrote The Castle of Otranto during a period of political turmoil and despairing over the future. Immersed in politics and facing unfair accusations, he may have felt that the morality and innate goodness of the Gothic era had diminished in modern society. This is evident in several characters, such as Frederic. Before meeting Frederic, the reader recognizes chivalric traits in his description:

The description of Frederic includes many traditional chivalric images; he is a prince, has suffered tragedy, and is presumed to have been killed by infidels. The figure of the "gallant and courteous Knight" is exaggerated, introducing the soon-to-be Gothic trope of excess (66).

Supply chain management is the flow of processes moving goods from the customer order to raw materials, supply, production, and distribution of products to the customer. The term supply chain management was coined in 1982 by consultant Keith Oliver. Keith Oliver described the overall process of planning, implementing, and controlling what happens in the supply chain to satisfy customers' needs in a timely and efficient manner. There are six key elements to a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers use these six key elements to provide the best customer service.

Production is the first step in the supply chain process. Production is the foundation for the entire supply chain process. The production stage will outline when, why, where, and how everything will be produced. Managers need to know what customers want. To know what customers want, managers can look at the market. The market is the biggest indicator to decide what the customer demands are. Once managers have analyzed the market and understand customer demand, they are ready to decide what products should be produced, and how many of those products should be produced. After the management has decided what is produced and how many, they are ready to decide where the products should be produced and at which plant will be best for volume and quality of good, keeping in mind customer demand and satisfaction must be met. After the location for production of the products has been decided, the next step is managers’ focus on scheduling workloads, and maintenance of equipment. Production is a very important step in the supply chain process. Every detail is vital throughout the whole process. If every detail is not planned accordingly, it could cost the company a lot of time and money in the long run. For example, I used to work at Wal-Mart and Target retail stores. Both companies have a designed layout for every entity of the business, from how an employee’s uniform should look to receiving shipments from trucks. Having outlined processes allow a company to work smoothly without confusion of direction and expectations.

The second key element in supply chain management is supply. Supply is defined as the strategic decisions that should be made to determine the core capabilities of a facility and outsourcing partnerships should grow from these decisions. A company may have many different divisions of production for a single product. All divisions consist of different equipment, workers, and specialties. The manager must decide which division is the best fit for the different processes of the product. Management may also decide to outsource the work to other companies. The core reason a manager would outsource the work to companies is to create velocity. Velocity is the ability to provide quality and flexibility while at the same time reducing costs or maintaining low cost levels.

Hitler is alive in Burma, the sign says.

Elliot Page, star of Juno, stands alone on a street corner holding a piece of cardboard with a disturbing message written on it with a Sharpie. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian country ruled by a tyrannical military junta that seized power in 1962 through a coup d'état. In 2007, several street protests took place, the first public protests in a decade. Led by a large number of Burmese monks, these protests became known as the "Saffron Revolution," named after the color of the monks' robes. Initially, the government reluctantly allowed the monks to gather peacefully, but violence soon escalated to what some considered an all-out war between the monks and the military junta, with the military actively invading and looting monasteries across the country. Foreign journalists were arrested on sight, including Kenji Nagai, a Japanese photojournalist who was killed on September 27, 2007, simply for being present at a street protest. While the official death toll stands at 13 killed, Colonel Hla Win, who defected from the army days before the official report, quoted, "Many more people have been killed in recent days than you’ve heard about. The bodies can be counted in several thousand."

This is nothing new. While these are some of the most recent examples of atrocities happening in our world, a government's desire to suppress dissent and maintain complete control over its citizens has existed as long as civilization itself. Early Roman emperors declared themselves chosen by the gods to have complete executive power over every aspect of their society. Japanese emperors are believed to be actual gods, sent to our world to lead their people to prosperity through the invention of Motorola cell phones and seppuku, and our current president, George W. Bush, has weekly conference calls with Ted Haggard, the leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subsidiary group of the Republican Party.

Some of the most well-known examples of these actions include the 1989 June 4th protest at Tiananmen Square, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students gathered to protest the authoritarian rule of the government. The death toll in that particular instance ranges wildly, with official reports from the Chinese government stating 200-300 dead to reports released by the Chinese Red Cross, declaring between 2,000-3,000 dead. Another example is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups, aided by the Rwandan government, began a systematic killing of all Tutsis, as well as political moderates, regardless of their ethnic backgrounds. Hitler's 'Third Reich' was a period spanning several years and several countries where anyone of Jewish background was rounded up and killed, another extreme example.

Duke Ellington's legacy in jazz stems mainly from his longevity and his ability to mold his orchestra creatively. While his presence on the piano is often understated in many of the pieces selected for this assignment, as a composer, Ellington excelled at creating rich and complex works that highlight the individual skills of his band members. He designed a framework that allowed soloists to improvise freely, while also writing tightly orchestrated phrases and arrangements that showcased the unique styles of his band members and emphasized the overall tone of the orchestra. This enabled him to compose some of the most innovative and brilliant pieces in jazz history.

The Grove Music dictionary highlights Ellington’s sound and innovation, particularly in the piece “Creole Love Call,” which uses the voice as a jazz instrument. This is an early example of Ellington’s use of voice to add texture and color without lyrics. “Creole Love Call” also demonstrates his ability to complement the style of his soloists, which is evident throughout his career. This slow, deliberate twelve-bar blues piece features six choruses:

1. Call and response between voice and reeds, starting smooth and melodic, then transitioning to a rougher sound towards the end.
2. Muted trumpet solo that elaborates on the basic melody and emphasizes several blue notes.
3. Sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, backed by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.
4. Full-band echoes the first chorus with a call and response by brass and reed sections.
5. The climactic chorus where reeds take the lead in a call and response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop-time from brass and rhythm sections.
6. A return to the structure of the first chorus, with call and response between voice and reeds, with the voice adopting the “growl” technique.

Ellington’s use of voice to add a tone color dimension to this piece is one example of a stylistic trait that permeates his work.

Later, in “Hot and Bothered,” recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill in tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response between “Bubber” Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing uses the vocal aspects of Miley’s playing and the instrumental elements of Cox’s voice to create a rich and complementary sound. “It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing)” extends these ideas, with Ellington utilizing Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton, a key member of his orchestra, to great effect in introducing the melody on muted trombone.

From a young age, she had felt a persistent longing for something intangible. This unfulfilled desire had begun around the age of 14 and remained with her even at 17. She had come to realize she desired a person rather than a material thing, yet no boy had sparked her interest. Despite several attempts by others, she remained uninterested. She often questioned her own nature, wondering what could cause this peculiar situation in a young girl. Years of introspection had yielded no satisfactory answers, so she continued living her life, constantly questioning her desires.

Generally, days at home were peaceful. Her parents were kind and calm, rarely arguing, even with their daughter. The only conflict arose when she asserted her independence and lively personality. She was the daughter of a peaceful couple, but her exuberance made her easily liked, along with her innate niceness.

Today, however, was different. As she moved from room to room, seeking inspiration, she heard a sudden scream from the kitchen. It was her mother's voice. She rushed in to find her mother lying on the floor, groaning in pain. She knelt beside her, "Mom? Mom, what's wrong?" Her mother, struggling to speak through the pain, asked her daughter to take her to the hospital. The daughter, grateful for her physical strength, carried her mother to the car and drove her to the hospital.

The hospital smelled of disinfectant and sickness, but her mind was focused solely on her mother. She rushed her to the doctors, who quickly took her to be examined. Her mother had fallen from a step stool while reaching for a vase in the highest cabinet.

This study aimed to demonstrate that adherence to a “Mediterranean Diet” (Med diet), indicated by a high “alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score”, is linked to a reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as lower stroke mortality. The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet, characterized by higher consumption of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats compared to saturated fats, and fish, with lower consumption of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol intake is allowed.

Previous prospective studies found an inverse association between adherence to a Med diet and risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality, and an intervention trial showed it to be more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and reducing the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals. Prior studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.

This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women aged 38 to 63, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states. Six times, from 1984 to 2004, the authors computed an aMed diet score from self-reported “food frequency questionnaires” (FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake during the preceding year. More than 95% of nurses maintained participation throughout the 20-year period. FFQs were validated through several studies. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed by review of medical or hospital records, autopsy, or death certificates. In cases where records were not available, “probable” cases were included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts so classified. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and use of postmenopausal hormones were calculated for each FFQ, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed.

To reduce random variation and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging together scores from two prior years). Adjustments were made for “confounders” (factors that could confuse the results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, use of postmenopausal hormones, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to assess the association between an aMed score and risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, indicated by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women. During the 20-year follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were identified. Women in the top aMed quintile had a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States of America suffered a devastating financial crisis. Unemployment rose, the housing market collapsed, and many of America’s most significant corporations were left in ruins. This recession continues to this day, so we must consider: what caused this crisis, and how can we prevent it? In brief, the financial crisis was brought about by selfish and naive political decisions that forced banks and companies to issue subprime loans into an immature and insufficient financial system. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwrite and repack these mortgages into CDOs and CDSs. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, banks faced a shortage of capital reserves and passed this chaos on to the repackaged mortgages they had sold, and eventually to the rest of the economy.

The financial crisis can be traced back to 1999 during the Clinton era, as the president sought reelection. To boost his popularity, he relaxed lending restrictions, setting the stage for the subprime crisis seven years later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation’s largest home mortgage underwriter, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans to low and moderate-income people and felt pressure from shareholders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes later warned, “But the government-subsidized corporation may face trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As the introduction details, and as Holmes predicted, ill-advised lending would inevitably lead to the collapse of the economy.

Numerous factors contributed to the economic downturn, one of which was the new and complex mortgage structure. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) were heavily used in the years leading up to the crisis, further entangling various sectors of the economy in the housing market. This led to excessive leverage by U.S. households and financial markets in the housing market, making them extremely sensitive to even small price fluctuations.

Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and financial institutions that held mortgage-backed securities were severely impacted. The top five U.S. investment banks collectively reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debt in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold cheaply, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subject to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were left with $5 trillion in mortgage debt and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition. That is the part of your story where you spread your writer's wings and take flight, leaving everyone amazed with your magnetic, even magical prose. Or the part where your readers fall asleep or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name. Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in a fun way.

Exposition is no friend of yours.

My dear readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still gets stuck in long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much. Exposition is the little devil on your shoulder telling you to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil on the other shoulder urging you to tell your audience every single detail of each character's childhood).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple language. In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a long monologue of information, like in "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In fiction, it's the author doing the telling.

Let me give you an example. While reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at a certain place and time, that they were married in a grand fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes. You wouldn't expect this entire episode to take two pages, during which both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each. You would expect the author to spend time on the husband's character, showing through his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would expect the heroine to demonstrate through big and small ways how his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story later tells you straight out that this was the case). A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally invested in his fate and gain insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts, beliefs, and dreams as seen through his eyes, and so on. You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect substance on the bare bones of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that substance. (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*) Sometimes it's tempting to rush past certain things. Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday, and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first one, which was live, was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man named Shad Hostettler from Ashley, Ohio, who had stabbed his wife. Her name was not mentioned, but his mug shot showed a man who looked like pure evil. Only two minutes were devoted to this story as it was still developing. They only provided that he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they spent an appropriate amount of time on this story.

The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, 18, who was critically injured in the Sharon Woods area. There had been no arrests at the time or any suspects. The SWAT team was investigating the crime. This story seemed short, and I believe it might have been due to the fact that it involved a "black" man or a black neighborhood. I've noticed over the years that minorities are often glossed over when they are victims of a crime. For instance, if a "white" child or adult is kidnapped or a victim of a crime, the media goes crazy; but if it's a minority person, they're lucky if it's even mentioned.

The next story was about a bullet hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about the incident's location.
