Both companies have a designed layout for every entity of the business, from how an employee’s uniform should look to receiving shipments from trucks. Having outlined processes allow a company to work smoothly without confusion of direction and expectations.

The second key element in supply chain management is supply. Supply is defined as the strategic decisions that should be made to determine the core capabilities of a facility and outsourcing partnerships should grow from these decisions. A company may have many different divisions of production for a single product. All divisions consist of different equipment, workers, and specialties. The manager must decide which division is the best fit for the different processes of the product. Management may also decide to outsource the work to other companies. The core reason a manager would outsource the work to companies is to create velocity. Velocity is the ability to provide quality and flexibility while at the same time reducing costs or maintaining low cost levels.

Hitler is alive in Burma, the sign says.

Elliot Page, star of Juno, stands alone on a street corner holding a piece of cardboard with a disturbing message written on it with a Sharpie. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian country ruled by a tyrannical military junta that seized power in 1962 through a coup d'état. In 2007, several street protests took place, the first public protests in a decade. Led by a large number of Burmese monks, these protests became known as the "Saffron Revolution," named after the color of the monks' robes. Initially, the government reluctantly allowed the monks to gather peacefully, but violence soon escalated to what some considered an all-out war between the monks and the military junta, with the military actively invading and looting monasteries across the country. Foreign journalists were arrested on sight, including Kenji Nagai, a Japanese photojournalist who was killed on September 27, 2007, simply for being present at a street protest. While the official death toll stands at 13 killed, Colonel Hla Win, who defected from the army days before the official report, quoted, "Many more people have been killed in recent days than you’ve heard about. The bodies can be counted in several thousand."

This is nothing new. While these are some of the most recent examples of atrocities happening in our world, a government's desire to suppress dissent and maintain complete control over its citizens has existed as long as civilization itself. Early Roman emperors declared themselves chosen by the gods to have complete executive power over every aspect of their society. Japanese emperors are believed to be actual gods, sent to our world to lead their people to prosperity through the invention of Motorola cell phones and seppuku, and our current president, George W. Bush, has weekly conference calls with Ted Haggard, the leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subsidiary group of the Republican Party.

Some of the most well-known examples of these actions include the 1989 June 4th protest at Tiananmen Square, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students gathered to protest the authoritarian rule of the government. The death toll in that particular instance ranges wildly, with official reports from the Chinese government stating 200-300 dead to reports released by the Chinese Red Cross, declaring between 2,000-3,000 dead. Another example is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups, aided by the Rwandan government, began a systematic killing of all Tutsis, as well as political moderates, regardless of their ethnic backgrounds. Hitler's 'Third Reich' was a period spanning several years and several countries where anyone of Jewish background was rounded up and killed, another extreme example.

Duke Ellington's legacy in jazz stems mainly from his longevity and his ability to mold his orchestra creatively. While his presence on the piano is often understated in many of the pieces selected for this assignment, as a composer, Ellington excelled at creating rich and complex works that highlight the individual skills of his band members. He designed a framework that allowed soloists to improvise freely, while also writing tightly orchestrated phrases and arrangements that showcased the unique styles of his band members and emphasized the overall tone of the orchestra. This enabled him to compose some of the most innovative and brilliant pieces in jazz history.

The Grove Music dictionary highlights Ellington’s sound and innovation, particularly in the piece “Creole Love Call,” which uses the voice as a jazz instrument. This is an early example of Ellington’s use of voice to add texture and color without lyrics. “Creole Love Call” also demonstrates his ability to complement the style of his soloists, which is evident throughout his career. This slow, deliberate twelve-bar blues piece features six choruses:

1. Call and response between voice and reeds, starting smooth and melodic, then transitioning to a rougher sound towards the end.
2. Muted trumpet solo that elaborates on the basic melody and emphasizes several blue notes.
3. Sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, backed by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.
4. Full-band echoes the first chorus with a call and response by brass and reed sections.
5. The climactic chorus where reeds take the lead in a call and response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop-time from brass and rhythm sections.
6. A return to the structure of the first chorus, with call and response between voice and reeds, with the voice adopting the “growl” technique.

Ellington’s use of voice to add a tone color dimension to this piece is one example of a stylistic trait that permeates his work.

Later, in “Hot and Bothered,” recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill in tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response between “Bubber” Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing uses the vocal aspects of Miley’s playing and the instrumental elements of Cox’s voice to create a rich and complementary sound. “It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing)” extends these ideas, with Ellington utilizing Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton, a key member of his orchestra, to great effect in introducing the melody on muted trombone.

From a young age, she had felt a persistent longing for something intangible. This unfulfilled desire had begun around the age of 14 and remained with her even at 17. She had come to realize she desired a person rather than a material thing, yet no boy had sparked her interest. Despite several attempts by others, she remained uninterested. She often questioned her own nature, wondering what could cause this peculiar situation in a young girl. Years of introspection had yielded no satisfactory answers, so she continued living her life, constantly questioning her desires.

Generally, days at home were peaceful. Her parents were kind and calm, rarely arguing, even with their daughter. The only conflict arose when she asserted her independence and lively personality. She was the daughter of a peaceful couple, but her exuberance made her easily liked, along with her innate niceness.

Today, however, was different. As she moved from room to room, seeking inspiration, she heard a sudden scream from the kitchen. It was her mother's voice. She rushed in to find her mother lying on the floor, groaning in pain. She knelt beside her, "Mom? Mom, what's wrong?" Her mother, struggling to speak through the pain, asked her daughter to take her to the hospital. The daughter, grateful for her physical strength, carried her mother to the car and drove her to the hospital.

The hospital smelled of disinfectant and sickness, but her mind was focused solely on her mother. She rushed her to the doctors, who quickly took her to be examined. Her mother had fallen from a step stool while reaching for a vase in the highest cabinet.

This study aimed to demonstrate that adherence to a “Mediterranean Diet” (Med diet), indicated by a high “alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score”, is linked to a reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as lower stroke mortality. The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet, characterized by higher consumption of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats compared to saturated fats, and fish, with lower consumption of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol intake is allowed.

Previous prospective studies found an inverse association between adherence to a Med diet and risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality, and an intervention trial showed it to be more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and reducing the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals. Prior studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.

This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women aged 38 to 63, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states. Six times, from 1984 to 2004, the authors computed an aMed diet score from self-reported “food frequency questionnaires” (FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake during the preceding year. More than 95% of nurses maintained participation throughout the 20-year period. FFQs were validated through several studies. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed by review of medical or hospital records, autopsy, or death certificates. In cases where records were not available, “probable” cases were included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts so classified. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and use of postmenopausal hormones were calculated for each FFQ, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed.

To reduce random variation and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging together scores from two prior years). Adjustments were made for “confounders” (factors that could confuse the results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, use of postmenopausal hormones, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to assess the association between an aMed score and risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, indicated by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women. During the 20-year follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were identified. Women in the top aMed quintile had a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States of America suffered a devastating financial crisis. Unemployment rose, the housing market collapsed, and many of America’s most significant corporations were left in ruins. This recession continues to this day, so we must consider: what caused this crisis, and how can we prevent it? In brief, the financial crisis was brought about by selfish and naive political decisions that forced banks and companies to issue subprime loans into an immature and insufficient financial system. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwrite and repack these mortgages into CDOs and CDSs. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, banks faced a shortage of capital reserves and passed this chaos on to the repackaged mortgages they had sold, and eventually to the rest of the economy.

The financial crisis can be traced back to 1999 during the Clinton era, as the president sought reelection. To boost his popularity, he relaxed lending restrictions, setting the stage for the subprime crisis seven years later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation’s largest home mortgage underwriter, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans to low and moderate-income people and felt pressure from shareholders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes later warned, “But the government-subsidized corporation may face trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As the introduction details, and as Holmes predicted, ill-advised lending would inevitably lead to the collapse of the economy.

Numerous factors contributed to the economic downturn, one of which was the new and complex mortgage structure. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) were heavily used in the years leading up to the crisis, further entangling various sectors of the economy in the housing market. This led to excessive leverage by U.S. households and financial markets in the housing market, making them extremely sensitive to even small price fluctuations.

Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and financial institutions that held mortgage-backed securities were severely impacted. The top five U.S. investment banks collectively reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debt in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold cheaply, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subject to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were left with $5 trillion in mortgage debt and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition. That is the part of your story where you spread your writer's wings and take flight, leaving everyone amazed with your magnetic, even magical prose. Or the part where your readers fall asleep or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name. Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in a fun way.

Exposition is no friend of yours.

My dear readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still gets stuck in long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much. Exposition is the little devil on your shoulder telling you to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil on the other shoulder urging you to tell your audience every single detail of each character's childhood).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple language. In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a long monologue of information, like in "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In fiction, it's the author doing the telling.

Let me give you an example. While reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at a certain place and time, that they were married in a grand fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes. You wouldn't expect this entire episode to take two pages, during which both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each. You would expect the author to spend time on the husband's character, showing through his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would expect the heroine to demonstrate through big and small ways how his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story later tells you straight out that this was the case). A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally invested in his fate and gain insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts, beliefs, and dreams as seen through his eyes, and so on. You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect substance on the bare bones of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that substance. (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*) Sometimes it's tempting to rush past certain things. Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday, and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first one, which was live, was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man named Shad Hostettler from Ashley, Ohio, who had stabbed his wife. Her name was not mentioned, but his mug shot showed a man who looked like pure evil. Only two minutes were devoted to this story as it was still developing. They only provided that he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they spent an appropriate amount of time on this story.

The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, 18, who was critically injured in the Sharon Woods area. There had been no arrests at the time or any suspects. The SWAT team was investigating the crime. This story seemed short, and I believe it might have been due to the fact that it involved a "black" man or a black neighborhood. I've noticed over the years that minorities are often glossed over when they are victims of a crime. For instance, if a "white" child or adult is kidnapped or a victim of a crime, the media goes crazy; but if it's a minority person, they're lucky if it's even mentioned.

The next story was about a bullet hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about the incident's location. It was determined that it was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle that hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for tips leading to the arrest of the shooter.

The next story was about the rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said the temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The length of the story was a bit short, but they used it as a "teaser" to keep viewers tuned in.

They also reported a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said it was a dark-skinned black man who robbed the store. He was wearing a hoodie sweatshirt, was about six feet tall, and weighed about 150 pounds. I thought they spent an unusual amount of time emphasizing his race and the darkness of his skin.

Another story was about a Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas drug kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute large amounts of marijuana from Texas to Ohio. One curious thing I noted was that instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison, they said "300" months. I'm not sure what the angle was, whether they thought that sounded harsher or what. They also mentioned he was Hispanic, but I don't believe that was really relevant to the story.

Brothers share an unbreakable bond, an unassailable connection. This bond is filled with emotions like love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, among others. Brothers understand each other more deeply than anyone else can, and when they look at their brother, they often see a reflection of themselves. It is in dire situations that the true nature of this bond becomes apparent, whether it is for good or ill. When these emotions are laid bare, they often come with great cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal bond is dealing with the consequences they bring. When one can look into their brother's eyes and see oneself, they see themselves not as others perceive them, but as they truly are. Their actions and the consequences of those actions reveal their true character. In "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers explore this theme, along with the intense emotions that surround it. In a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. In the climactic scene, bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride, and only one brother survives. The theme is expressed through the direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator's point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which greatly influence his actions.

The protagonist's actions can be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his younger brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist harbors resentment towards Doodle. He wanted a brother he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could be someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn… These things were obviously impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with a weak heart, making it unlikely he would even survive. Even if he did, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. For the young protagonist, filled with wild fantasies, this was a devastating blow. He even began to contemplate killing Doodle by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would think of infanticide? However, his heart softened when the small child smiled at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist so much hope! This shows that his conviction probably wasn't very strong. Deep down, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complex, creative information-processing system. As technology has evolved from primitive to modern, so have the metaphors used to describe the brain. Initially, it was likened to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. Keep in mind that while these metaphors are helpful, they can also lead to misinterpretations.

Information processing begins with sensory organs, which convert physical stimuli like touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The brain processes this sensory information through both bottom-up and top-down processing. For instance, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing combines simple information like color, orientation, and object edges to recognize a box. Top-down processing uses these decisions to speed up identifying the box as a black box rather than a hole.

Once processed, an attention filter determines the importance of the signal and which cognitive processes to make available. For example, while your brain processes every blade of grass when looking down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. Conversely, you might pick out your name in a noisy room. There are multiple stages of processing, and the results are repeatedly modulated by attention.

In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are different types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded, with specific methods for each type of sensory stimulus. For instance, verbal input can be encoded structurally (how the printed word looks), phonemically (how the word sounds), or semantically (what the word means). Once stored, information must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which holds information for around 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through specific neurons. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained by the structure of certain proteins.

There are various models of how knowledge is organized in the brain, including those based on human memory retrieval, computer science, and neurophysiology. The semantic network model proposes that concepts are nodes, and these nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, "chair" might be linked to "table," which can be linked to "wooden," and so on.

Aldous Huxley criticizes the emerging threat of both technology and the capitalist system in his novel Brave New World. The society values collective happiness above individuality and conditions its citizens from birth to pursue pleasure above all else. Citizens are mere tools in the scheme of the World Controller, who imposes a single ideology. Through the lens of Marxist philosophy, one can discern Huxley's skepticism about these systems. Terms like homogenization and reification reinforce the idea that the novel critiques the flaws of the emerging economy of its time.

Capitalism is satirized through the Marxist concept of false consciousness, where the common people are kept unaware of their true economic relationships. This is achieved through ideological control of the working class and laborers, evident in the conditioning of the people in Brave New World. The lower classes, Delta, Gamma, etc., have no genuine will of their own; their desire to consume and indulge is strengthened by hypnopædia, controlled by the World Controller. This manipulation is an example of hegemony, where a dominant group controls the lower classes, who unknowingly support this structure. The upper classes are aware of this manipulation but do not act. Few Alphas or Betas, like Bernard, do more than accept their place. The interactions between social classes reveal the oppression of capitalism.

In Brave New World, there is no genuine relationship between individuals. Characters, even major ones, lack depth. Perhaps Huxley suggests that the rise of technology and capitalism takes away people's free will and expression. Love and extreme emotions are absent, with interactions kept superficial, as seen in men's comments about women's physical appearance and women's comments about their sexual encounters. Each class's complacency with its status in the hierarchy reflects the socioeconomic effects of capitalism. Their obedience to their role in the community is evidence of Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are made to feel superior as long as they continue to consume, obey, and conform to their peers.

I have studied at University Park for about two and a half years, or approximately four and a half semesters. For many people, including myself, navigating the campus can be challenging. During my freshman year, I lived in an East Halls dormitory, which was the easternmost residence hall on campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Walking from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in distant locations like the Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes, especially in bad weather, as it often is in State College. An alumni slightly older than me mentioned that not long ago, the East Halls dorms were separated from the rest of the school by vast stretches of unused land. Today, that empty space is filled with sports fields, new buildings including the new Creamery and health services building, and surrounded by apartments. As our campus continues to expand, traveling from one location to another becomes increasingly difficult. What is the best solution to the problem of mobility on a college campus? The bicycle is often the best option. However, having a bike alone won't solve any problems. Students need to use them, and the campus infrastructure should accommodate bicyclists.

I recently discussed this with a friend who had resumed bicycling after a few years. He remarked that he wondered why he ever stopped. “Bikes are great,” he said, “for a few years, it wasn’t trendy to ride a bike, but it’s the only practical way to get around.” In addition to being beneficial for your health, bicycling is the most efficient mode of transportation. A bowl of oatmeal and a bit of physical effort can take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus, just as far from the center of campus as certain dorms. This year, the smartest decision I made was to buy a bike. Every day, I have class in Thomas building, which is at least a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can reduce that time to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only issue is that Pollock Road offers the most direct route to Thomas building from my house, and it isn't always an easy path to traverse by bike or on foot. While walking also has its merits, I'm too busy to walk. If I didn’t have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option for getting to class. Walking to Thomas every day would add an extra 30-40 minutes to my day. That’s over two and a half hours every week. Plus, all the time I'd need to spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, and so on would consume more time than I can spare.
